    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1916-12-02T14:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1916-12-02T14:00:00-05:00" n="418"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d418">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 300.115C42/3</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in Austria-Hungary</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_PFC1" type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Penfield</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1916-12-02T14:00:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">December 2, 1916, 2 p. m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1436. Department advised from affidavits of crew that United States S. S. <hi
                        rend="italic">Chemung</hi> was sunk by gunfire and torpedo by Austrian
                    submarine November 26, 10.20 a. m., at 36° 37´ north, 1° 55´ west. Vessel bound
                    from New York to Genoa with mixed cargo.</p>
                <p>Bring case to attention of Foreign Minister, with request for immediate
                    investigation and report on this sinking of an American vessel.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_LR1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Lansing</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
                <postscript>
                    <p>[For statement of the American Government’s decision not to join the European
                        neutral governments in a conference for the consideration of problems of
                        neutral rights and duties, see circular telegram, December 4, 1916, 4 p. m.
                        to diplomatic officers in European countries, <hi rend="italic">post</hi>,
                            <ref target="#pg_696">page 696</ref>.]</p>
                </postscript>
            </div>
        </body>
